WHUDO
Dorm OS

An AI-powered smart dormitory system for Wuhan University — where four roommates share one intelligent space.

Role
UI Designer
Scope
Concept · AI · UI Design
Platform
Smart Panel / Tablet
Context
Wuhan University · WHU Design Course
01 Problem Space

Dorm life is shared.
But control isn't.

Four people. One room. Dozens of devices. No system to manage them together — until now.

01
No shared device controlEach roommate controls devices separately, leading to conflicts over AC temperature, lights, and noise.
02
Static interfaces, zero contextExisting smart home apps don't adapt to sleep schedules, study sessions, or weather — every setting is manual.
03
No memory, no careFour years of shared life disappear the moment you move out. No system captures those moments.
Design Goal

Build a smart dorm OS that unifies device control, adapts to individual habits, and holds shared memories — making the dorm a living system, not just a collection of appliances.

AI-Driven Multi-User Context-Aware Emotionally Warm
02 Target Users

Designed for
Z-Gen dormers

Core users: Wuhan University undergrads living in 4-person dorms. High digital literacy, high desire for personalization, used to negotiating shared spaces.

📚
The Night Owl
Stays up late studying. Needs the desk lamp on without disturbing sleeping roommates. Wants system to learn her schedule automatically.
🌡️
The Temperature Negotiator
Always fighting over AC settings. Wants transparent usage records and fair anonymous voting so no one feels singled out.
🎓
The Senior About to Graduate
4 years of shared life, countless late nights. Wants a way to remember all of it — not just photos, but the rhythm of daily life together.
03 Information Architecture

Five modules,
one coherent flow

From face recognition to graduation memoir — every interaction is mapped to a real moment in dorm life.

04 Screen Design

Every screen
tells a story

16 screens across 6 modules, designed with WHU's sage-green palette. Light mode for day, dark for night.

Module 01 Recognition
Face Recognition — Welcome Home
The entry point. Large clock, centered recognition animation. On success, a personalized greeting appears by name. Failure routes to PIN backup. Long-press to enter Guest Mode.
Face recognition in progress · 人脸识别中
Recognition success · 周思雯，晚上好
Module 02 Home Dashboard
Dashboard + AI Voice Assistant
The control center: device status, one-tap mode switching (Study / Sleep / Social / Away), real-time environment data, upcoming tasks, and the AI voice assistant. Everything in one view.
Home · Study mode active
AI assistant overlay · "我困了"
Home · Night mode variant
Module 03 User Management
Identity, History & Roommate Awareness
Each roommate has a profile with AI-generated usage titles ("Night Owl", "Dorm DJ"). Shows who used the room and when — building shared accountability without surveillance.
User page · 周思雯（熬夜达人）
Roommate birthday reminder · anonymous voting entry
Module 04 Device Control
Granular Control + AI Recommendations
Per-device fine control with zone assignment (bed area / study area / balcony). AI generates personalized recommendations based on weather + usage history. "Accept / Adjust / Cancel" in one tap.
AC control · AI recommendation card
Zone lighting control · 正在由周思雯控制中
Device control · night variant
Module 05 Stats & Reminders
Usage Insights + Gentle Nudges
Weekly device usage charts, personalized habit summaries ("You usually turn on the desk lamp at 21:30"), and contextual reminders. The system learns to anticipate before you ask.
Stats · "学习灯开了6小时，要不要闭眼5分钟？"
My habits panel · weekly trend chart
Module 06 Settings + Graduation Memoir
The Farewell Easter Egg
Standard settings panel, plus a hidden graduation feature: as you approach graduation, WHUDO compiles your 4 years of usage logs, roommate interactions, and seasonal memories into a shareable PDF memoir.
Settings · system management panel
Graduation Memoir · "保存互动记录，一键共享"

05 Design Highlights

What makes
WHUDO different

Five design decisions that go beyond functional — building a system that feels like it understands how people actually live together.

🎯
Anonymous Voting for Shared Decisions
When roommates disagree on lights-out time, WHUDO runs a real-time anonymous vote. No awkward conversations, no one singled out — the room decides together.
🤖
Behavior-Driven AI Recommendations
The system learns individual preferences over time — suggesting "26°C tonight" based on past patterns and weather API data, not generic defaults. Users can accept, adjust, or decline.
🏆
Playful Usage Titles as Social Glue
"Night Owl", "Dorm DJ", "冷感之神" — AI-generated titles based on real usage. Turns data into personality, and creates shared language between roommates.
📕
Graduation Memoir — 4 Years in a PDF
The most emotionally resonant feature: a system that generates a memory book from 4 years of shared interactions. WHUDO doesn't just manage your dorm — it remembers it.
🌙
Contextual Night Mode
After 22:00, the interface shifts to low-brightness blue-grey. Not just a color scheme change — device recommendations also shift to quiet, sleep-friendly defaults automatically.
🔒
Transparent Control, Protected Privacy
Usage records show who controlled what — building shared accountability. But voting is anonymous, and personal health data stays per-user only. Designed for trust, not surveillance.
06 Visual Language

WHU sage green
meets calm intelligence

The visual system extends WHU's campus color identity into a digital interface that feels both institutional and warm. Rounded corners, generous whitespace, and soft shadows create a dorm-appropriate lightness.

07 Reflection

What I learned
building this

A concept project that taught me how to think about multi-user systems, shared spaces, and the emotional layer of product design.

What worked well

  • Grounding every feature in a real dorm scenario (not abstract "smart home" tropes) kept the design focused
  • The anonymous voting mechanism solved a genuine shared-living tension without adding friction
  • The graduation memoir feature emerged from asking "what happens at the end?" — backward design from emotional moments
  • Night mode as a behavioral shift (not just visual) reflects real user context

If I were to iterate

  • Build an actual clickable prototype in Figma to test the multi-user switching flow
  • Run user testing on the AI recommendation acceptance rate — does "accept/adjust/cancel" feel right?
  • Validate the privacy/transparency balance with real roommates through interviews
  • Explore IoT integration feasibility with actual WHU campus infrastructure
  • Test whether gamified usage titles feel fun or invasive in practice
